  <h2 id="system-setup">Lubricating Oil Centrifuge System Setup</h2>

  <div class="mb-6">
    <img
      src="/images/lube-oil-centrifuge/Lube-Oil-Centrifuge-System.webp"
      alt="Lube Oil Centrifuge System Diagram"
      loading="lazy"
      width="600"
      height="463"
      class="img-cap-600"
    />
    <p class="text-xs text-text-muted mt-2 text-center"><strong>Lube Oil Centrifuge System Diagram</strong></p>
  </div>

  <p>
    Lubricating oil purifiers are often installed in a 'kidney loop' arrangement. The diagram above shows the typical arrangement for this system.
  </p>

  <p>
    A pump feeds the contaminated oil to the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oil_purification">lube oil centrifuge</a> through an electric heater. Pre-heating the oil reduces the viscosity. Lower viscosity leads to high separation efficiency from the purifier. The lube oil centrifuge separates the free water and solids (down to 0.5&mu;).
  </p>

  <p>
    The separated water drains out of the centrifuge, and the separated solids accumulate in the centrifuge bowl. The operator removes the sludge manually in a 'manual clean' centrifuge. A 'self-cleaning' Alfa Laval centrifuge automatically ejects the separated sludge.
  </p>

